d372 1
a372 1
<h2>1.9 - What is new in OpenBSD 5.5?</h2>
d375 3
a377 3
The complete list of changes made to OpenBSD 5.4 to create OpenBSD 5.5
can be found on <a href="../plus55.html">plus55.html</a>, and highlights
on the <a href="../55.html">OpenBSD 5.5 Information page</a>, however
d379 1
a379 1
warrant some special note to people upgrading or installing OpenBSD 5.5
d384 7
a390 2
<li><b>Renamed platform:</b><br>
OpenBSD/beagle was renamed <a href="../armv7">armv7</a> after 5.4.
d396 16
a411 17
<li><b>Year 2038 ready!</b><br>
OpenBSD has switched its <tt>time_t</tt> to 64 bit.  New installs will
not be an issue, but <a href="upgrade55.html">upgrades</a> will have a
have to unload all packages before the upgrade and re-install
afterwards.

<li><b>Releases and packages are now cryptographically signed</b>
with the
<a href="http://www.openbsd.org/cgi-bin/man.cgi?query=signify&amp;sektion=1">signify(1)</a> utility.
<ul>
<li>The installer will verify all sets before installing.
<li>Installing without verification works, but is discouraged.
<li>Users are advised to verify the installer (bsd.rd, install55.iso, etc.)
    ahead of time using the
    <a href="http://www.openbsd.org/cgi-bin/man.cgi?query=signify&sektion=1#end">signify(1)</a> tool if available.
<li><a href="http://www.openbsd.org/cgi-bin/man.cgi?query=pkg_add&amp;sektion=1">pkg_add(1)</a> now trusts signed packages only by default.
</ul>
d413 2
a414 8
<li><b>Installer is now scriptable</b>, using an
<a href="http://www.openbsd.org/cgi-bin/man.cgi?query=autoinstall&sektion=8">auto-installation</a>
process.

<li><b>New install images:</b><br>
miniroot55.fs is bootable with bsd.rd only, install55.fs also has all
the install sets (unsigned).
These files can be written to a USB (or other) media.
d437 1
a437 1
done on laptops.
a477 7

<!-- XXX apache gone in 5.6 -->
<li><i>Why isn't a newer version of Apache included?</i><br>
The license on newer versions is unacceptable.
Users interested in more modern web servers are encouraged to look at
<a href="http://www.openbsd.org/cgi-bin/man.cgi?query=nginx&amp;sektion=8">nginx(8)</a>
which will be replacing Apache in base in OpenBSD 5.6.
