<h2>1.9 - What is new in OpenBSD 3.6?</h2>
d341 5
a345 5
The complete list of changes made to OpenBSD 3.5 to create OpenBSD 3.6
can be found <a href="../plus36.html">here</a>, however here are some
changes the OpenBSD team anticipate will require some special note to
people upgrading or installing OpenBSD 3.6 who are familiar with older
versions:
d348 34
a381 31
<li><b>Symmetrical MultiProcessor (SMP) support is here for
i386/amd64!</b>
A separate kernel (<tt>bsd.mp</tt>) is provided for SMP operation.

<li><b>Incorporation of a Network Time Protocol daemon
(<a href="http://www.openbsd.org/cgi-bin/man.cgi?query=ntpd&amp;sektion=8">ntpd</a>)
in the base system.</b>
As one might expect, this daemon was designed to be solid, secure and
free.
It is also fairly simple to use, and is expected to satisfy the
majority of the users needing NTP services.
If you are currently using the ntpd from
<a href="faq8.html#Ports">ports</a>, you will probably wish to look at
this new program as a possible alternative.
Upgraders will need to be aware you may end up with two ntpd programs
and make sure you are running the one you desire.

<li><b>New users and groups.</b>
Several new users and groups have been added to OpenBSD due to
privilege separation.
Upgraders will have to be sure to update their <tt>/etc</tt>
directory carefully to incorporate them, as directed on
<a href="upgrade36.html">upgrade36.html</a>.

<li><b>New CD booting system.</b>
Traditionally, OpenBSD booted from CD using "floppy emulation".
This limited the install kernel size to 2.88M, and not all 
computers would boot a 2.88M emulation CDROM.
It is hoped the new "non-emulation" booting will allow the 
CD to be bootable in many newer computers that would not 
boot the earlier CDROMs.
a442 5
<li><i>Why isn't XFree86 v4.4 included?</i>
The changes to the license in v4.4 are unacceptable, and thus, along
with many other major open source software projects, OpenBSD is holding
at the last free version, which is "almost" v4.4.

d470 1
a470 1
